{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "GasDiffusionTimescale",
        "description": "Characteristic timescale for gas-phase diffusion of a species to an aerosol particle ŌĆö Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 12, Eq. 12.49. The gas-phase diffusion timescale Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g) is the characteristic time for a gas-phase concentration perturbation to diffuse to the surface of a particle of radius R_p, given the gas-phase molecular diffusivity D_g of the species. It is one of the family of mass-transfer timescales in Ch. 12 ŌĆö gas-phase diffusion, interfacial transport, aqueous-phase diffusion, aqueous-phase reaction ŌĆö that are compared against one another to identify the rate-limiting step in gas-to-particle conversion: a short Žä_dg means gas-phase diffusion is fast and not the bottleneck. The timescale grows quadratically with the particle radius and inversely with the diffusivity. Migrated from Aerosol.jl GasDiffusionTimescale.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch12",
            "timescales",
            "mass-transfer"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "GasDiffusionTimescale": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 12. Gas-phase diffusion timescale: Eq. 12.49.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/timescales.jl:14\n\nUpstream `GasDiffusionTimescale` is an MTK `@component` (no parameterization). It declares two scalar `@parameters` ŌĆö `R_p` (particle radius, m, default 1.0e-5) and `D_g` (gas-phase diffusivity, m^2/s, default 2.0e-5) ŌĆö and one scalar `@variable` `Žä_dg` (gas-phase diffusion timescale, s). The single equation is `Žä_dg ~ R_p^2 / (4 * D_g)` ŌĆö Eq. 12.49 of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 12: the characteristic time for a gas-phase concentration perturbation to diffuse to the particle surface.\n\nObserved classification: GasDiffusionTimescale has no `D()` time-derivative anywhere ŌĆö it is a purely-algebraic component. `Žä_dg` is an algebraic output (`Žä_dg ~ R_p^2/(4┬ĘD_g)`). After MTK `mtkcompile` / `structural_simplify` the compiled system has zero ODE states and `Žä_dg` becomes an observed quantity. It is therefore serialized as `type: observed` with an `expression` (not `type: state` with an equation), and the `equations` array is empty, matching the sibling pure-algebraic timescale migration `aqueous_eq.esm` (src/timescales.jl:183) and the other pure-algebraic Aerosol.jl migrations `zsr.esm` and `critical_ssa.esm`.\n\nUnicode identifier `Žä_dg` is kept verbatim from the upstream `@variables` declaration; the ESM identifier pattern permits unicode and the sibling Aerosol.jl migrations (`aqueous_eq.esm`: `Žä_s`, `Žä_a`; `zsr.esm`: `╬▒_w`; `kelvin.esm`: `Žā`, `Žü_l`) keep Greek symbols, so no ASCII rename is applied. The ASCII parameter names `R_p` and `D_g` are likewise carried verbatim from the upstream `@parameters`; `R_p` does not collide with the reserved bare constant name `R` (universal gas constant).\n\nTests authored from physics: the upstream `timescales.jl` carries no test file (`has_tests: N` in the migration tracker). The inline `tests` block is authored from the closed-form Eq. 12.49 ŌĆö pinning the exact analytic value of `Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g)` at the upstream default parameterization, bracketing the quadratic dependence on the particle radius R_p on both sides of the default (radius doubled ŌåÆ timescale ├Ś4; radius halved ŌåÆ timescale ├Ę4), exercising the inverse dependence on the gas-phase diffusivity D_g (diffusivity doubled ŌåÆ timescale ├Ę2), the fast-diffusion limit of a fine accumulation-mode particle, and the R_p = 0 limit where the timescale vanishes.\n\nNot migrated: `timescales.jl` defines six independent `@component`s ŌĆö `GasDiffusionTimescale`, `AqueousDiffusionTimescale`, `InterfacialTimescale`, `ReactionTimescale`, `SolidEquilibrationTimescale`, and `AqueousEquilibrationTimescale`. Only `GasDiffusionTimescale` (src/timescales.jl:14) is in scope for this component migration; the other five are separate migration-tracker rows with their own target `.esm` files under `components/aerosol/timescales/`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8): the model is a single closed-form algebraic expression ŌĆö one squaring, one multiplication, and one division ŌĆö so float64 evaluation roundoff is at the 1-ULP (~1e-16 relative) level; rel=1e-8 leaves ample headroom. The `zero_radius_zero_timescale` test adds a tight per-assertion abs=1e-20 so a stuck-nonzero regression in the `Žä_dg` quotient cannot pass on the relative branch."
            },
            "variables": {
                "R_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.0e-5,
                    "description": "Particle radius ŌĆö the characteristic radius of the aerosol particle to which the gas-phase species diffuses (Eq. 12.49 term R_p). Sets the diffusion length scale; because the perturbation must spread across a distance comparable to R_p, the timescale grows as R_p┬▓."
                },
                "D_g": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "default": 2.0e-5,
                    "description": "Gas-phase (molecular) diffusivity of the species in air (Eq. 12.49 term D_g) ŌĆö sets the rate at which a gas-phase concentration perturbation spreads. A larger diffusivity propagates the perturbation to the particle surface faster and shortens the diffusion timescale."
                },
                "Žä_dg": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "s",
                    "description": "Gas-phase diffusion timescale (Eq. 12.49): Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g). The characteristic time for a gas-phase concentration perturbation to diffuse to the particle surface. Grows quadratically with the particle radius R_p and inversely with the gas-phase diffusivity D_g; when short relative to the interfacial, aqueous-diffusion and reaction timescales, gas-phase diffusion is not the rate-limiting step in gas-to-particle conversion.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    "R_p",
                                    2
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    4,
                                    "D_g"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08
            },
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_parameters",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.49 at the upstream default parameterization (R_p = 1e-5 m, D_g = 2e-5 m┬▓/s). The gas-phase diffusion timescale is Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g) = (1e-5)┬▓/(4┬Ę2e-5) = 1.25e-6 s ŌĆö a microsecond-scale time for a gas-phase concentration perturbation to diffuse to the particle surface. The output is algebraic and time-invariant, so the same value is asserted at t = 0 and t = 1.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.25e-6
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 1.0,
                            "expected": 1.25e-6
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "quadratic_in_radius",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.49 is quadratic in the particle radius R_p ŌĆö the diffusion length scale enters squared. Doubling R_p from the 1e-5 m default to 2e-5 m quadruples the gas-phase diffusion timescale from 1.25e-6 to Žä_dg = (2e-5)┬▓/(4┬Ę2e-5) = 5e-6 s: a larger particle presents a longer distance for the gas-phase perturbation to diffuse across.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 2.0e-5
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 5.0e-6
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "radius_halved_quarters_timescale",
                    "description": "The quadratic dependence of Eq. 12.49 acts downward as well: halving the particle radius R_p from the 1e-5 m default to 5e-6 m quarters the gas-phase diffusion timescale from 1.25e-6 to Žä_dg = (5e-6)┬▓/(4┬Ę2e-5) = 3.125e-7 s. Together with quadratic_in_radius this brackets the R_p┬▓ scaling on both sides of the default.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 5.0e-6
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 3.125e-7
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "inverse_in_diffusivity",
                    "description": "Eq. 12.49 varies inversely with the gas-phase diffusivity D_g. Doubling D_g from the 2e-5 m┬▓/s default to 4e-5 m┬▓/s halves the gas-phase diffusion timescale from 1.25e-6 to Žä_dg = (1e-5)┬▓/(4┬Ę4e-5) = 6.25e-7 s ŌĆö a faster-diffusing species spreads a concentration perturbation to the particle surface more quickly.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "D_g": 4.0e-5
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 6.25e-7
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "fine_particle_fast_diffusion",
                    "description": "For a fine accumulation-mode particle the quadratic R_p┬▓ scaling makes gas-phase diffusion extremely fast. With R_p = 1e-7 m (a 0.1 ┬Ąm radius, two decades below the coarse-particle default) and the default D_g = 2e-5 m┬▓/s, Žä_dg = (1e-7)┬▓/(4┬Ę2e-5) = 1.25e-10 s ŌĆö sub-nanosecond, confirming gas-phase diffusion is never the rate-limiting step for fine particles.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 1.0e-7
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.25e-10
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "zero_radius_zero_timescale",
                    "description": "Limiting case: with a vanishing particle radius (R_p = 0) there is no diffusion length scale and Žä_dg = 0 exactly ŌĆö the numerator R_p┬▓ vanishes while the denominator 4┬ĘD_g stays finite at the default D_g. A tight per-assertion absolute tolerance guards against a stuck-nonzero regression in the Žä_dg quotient.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 0.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "Žä_dg",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.0,
                            "tolerance": {
                                "abs": 1e-20
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "timescale_vs_radius",
                    "description": "The gas-phase diffusion timescale rises quadratically with the particle radius (Eq. 12.49). Sweeping R_p over the 1e-9ŌĆō1e-5 m range ŌĆö from a nucleation-mode cluster up to a coarse particle ŌĆö at the default D_g = 2e-5 m┬▓/s traces the parabola Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g): Žä_dg climbs four orders of magnitude for every two decades of radius.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_p",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-5,
                                    "count": 60,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_dg_vs_R_p",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Gas-phase diffusion timescale Žä_dg as a function of particle radius R_p (at the default D_g).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "R_p",
                                "label": "Particle radius R_p (m)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "Žä_dg",
                                "label": "Gas-phase diffusion timescale Žä_dg (s)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "timescale_vs_diffusivity",
                    "description": "The gas-phase diffusion timescale varies inversely with the gas-phase diffusivity (Eq. 12.49). With R_p at the default 1e-5 m, sweeping D_g over the 5e-6ŌĆō5e-5 m┬▓/s range ŌĆö the span of molecular diffusivities of trace gases in air ŌĆö traces the Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g) hyperbola: a faster-diffusing species reaches the particle surface sooner.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "D_g",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 5.0e-6,
                                    "stop": 5.0e-5,
                                    "count": 60,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_dg_vs_D_g",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Gas-phase diffusion timescale Žä_dg as a function of gas-phase diffusivity D_g (at the default R_p).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "D_g",
                                "label": "Gas-phase diffusivity D_g (m┬▓/s)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "Žä_dg",
                                "label": "Gas-phase diffusion timescale Žä_dg (s)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "timescale_radius_diffusivity_heatmap",
                    "description": "Joint dependence of the gas-phase diffusion timescale on the particle radius and the gas-phase diffusivity (Eq. 12.49). The heatmap of Žä_dg(R_p, D_g) shows the timescale rising steeply (quadratically) with R_p and falling with D_g ŌĆö the Žä_dg = R_p┬▓/(4┬ĘD_g) surface over the aerosol-size / gas-diffusivity plane.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_p",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 1.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-5,
                                    "count": 30,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "D_g",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 5.0e-6,
                                    "stop": 5.0e-5,
                                    "count": 25,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_dg_R_p_D_g_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "Žä_dg(R_p, D_g) heatmap over the aerosol-size / gas-diffusivity plane.",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "R_p",
                                "label": "Particle radius R_p (m)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "D_g",
                                "label": "Gas-phase diffusivity D_g (m┬▓/s)"
                            },
                            "value": {
                                "variable": "Žä_dg",
                                "reduce": "final"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
